Also, what gives us the right to dictate what weapon development another country partakes in as we do it ourselves. If we believe we have the right to defend ourselves, doesn't everyone? Also, to destroy the materials without clear insight into the motivations behind it, we are simply exercising power over another country. Isn't it likely that Iran would see this as a violation and sow unrest and resentment for the US that could have potentially more damaging consequences than simply testing and developing weapons? Iran isn't the only country that has nuclear abilities. Would we do the same thing to Russia or North Korea or China? What is different about our relationship with Iran? However, if there were confirmed information about the intentions of the weapons that would violate human rights or other international law, then perhaps the risk of preemptively destroying the resources is the best course of action to at least buy time to figure out a long term solution. I feel that to reach out and try civil communication and find agreement and establish restrictions/guidelines for accountability would be a more appropriate initial step. If we were to destroy some nuclear material, there's no reason to believe that they wouldn't be able to acquire more and continue, so it seems to me to be a short term solution to a larger issue. How would we respond if some foreign power did the same to us? The laws are put into place for a reason, we are not above them.
